<DIV2 TYPE="letter">
<PB N="23" REF="016334_0024_0F9C26C485091BB8">
<OPENER><DATELINE>Penn&s;borough,
<DATE>June 1, 1778.</DATE></DATELINE>
<SALUTE>SIR,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>THE charge under which you were arre&s;ted, is, refu&s;ing to comply with a general order, i&s;&s;ued expre&s;sly for the relief of the troops on piquet, founded in the nece&s;&s;ity o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> the ca&s;e, and which at that period could not have been otherwi&s;e remedied.</P>
<P>I was engaged in forwarding di&s;patches to colonels Hol|ling&s;worth, Rum&s;ey, and Pope, which prevented my &s;end|ing you the charge la&s;t night.</P>
<P>Was I di&s;po&s;ed to enter upon a replication to your billet it might with great propriety be ob&s;erved, that liberty often degenerates into licentiou&s;ne&s;s, and manly &s;pirit into petulancy, but my time might be better employed by a proper attention to my public duty.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>I am, SIR,
Your very obedient humble &s;ervant, W. SMALLWOOD.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
<TRAILER>Capt. Norwood.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
